Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other kinds of virtual currencies such as the "Credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also swap back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With bitcoin, all net knots are simultaneously the account holder, auditors, cash issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data relating to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are available in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that will be started on the computers, while the winner, who is a type of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding these additional lines.
This is a fragment of the file, i.e. converting a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add it a number before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that produces a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check that it is correct.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice as fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would not be connected because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably by the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided into a hundred million set, which leaves a certain amount of space...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the performance of the calculation.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked and the bitcoin entries were stolen.
"The weakness used does not relate to the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real-money payment company and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB shall also report on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, Bargund also points out this flaw.
Important actors such as Wikipedia reject donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the bill and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November a "mega-closure sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a wireless payment with a mobile phone, but Bitcoin uses to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide only one address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat, which assures that he has thousands of users.
It is a general trend to identify where hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontal-oriented systems.
"It will take some time to pass Bitcoin, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also envisages re-evaluation of the various risks currently considered to be high in the event of a success of this currency.
