A Constitution With the Breaking Bar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt, with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, remains more than ever divided, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional, multiple-changed text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal transition.
This new initiative has only provided for a stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president continues in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "break his word" and "the right to walk".
On the side of its advocates, it is ensured that there is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period that forces the brothers to abandon their plans to explain the text section for the Egyptians.
For the presidents, it is also a way to regain their public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is going down all over the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in good faith.
While the Egyptian people with this back attack are being put to an extreme vote: " Either you agree to my draft or I retain the unlimited authority," the latter should probably end after the constitution has been adopted.
85 most of the Islamic members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration, in mid-November they turned their backs on the view that they had not been able to apply their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted similarly.
In order to reach the decision-making capacity yesterday morning, 11 persons, deputy members, were added to all ranks.
Some are very close to the Muslims.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
The commentators also found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the hour of prayer, as some members of the board felt that the pendulum of the constitutional assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, is finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and says that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of the law".
The Salafist parties for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a more stringent application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
"Holiness" refers to the liberals who view this only as a propaganda blow.
Because according to them, Islamization of the Constitution is taking place on other articles.
In particular, they have been given Article 220 in the light of which the University of Al-Azhar has a consultative function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "those who are invited to an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here you can see the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next director of this university should be far less consistent than the present.
"At the present time, it is not a concrete religious commitment to be recognized.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," writes Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral work on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits, "that in relation to Article 220 there may be a plurality, since the terms used are derived from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, this refers to the "Fiqh" [Islamic Law, d.o.b.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil magistrates are competent to decide on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the extensive powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslims argue that these comparisons with the former regime have been significantly reduced.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have required.
The latter also share their concerns about the text they see as a threat to freedom.
The existence of blasphemism is maintained and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to free expression, especially for the press.
In addition, there is no longer an article on the protection of women, Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch underlines.
In your view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
