Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to a ministerial meeting of the member countries of the European Space Organisation ESA as the twentieth member of this Space Authority. Poland is thus the second member of the former East Block (to the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The way of Poland into space began freely much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos spiritists engaged in space travel, which they did not always understand.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thought from his pioneering work "Introductory to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomi had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Rep-Hirsch Prize, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelteria and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934, for "Enter into the Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel has been praised, among other things, for having been named after him one of the craters on the side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a railway station was built in Poland for which a rocket was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rockets should be used to start or brake the drains.
The information to this effect comes only from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-operated missiles.
The research work was conducted by the Institute of Komórka Techniki Uzfrijenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
It is apparent from the documents submitted that the research has progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted freely by the intrusion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, in the press of Ing. Rohoziński, the design of a photo-electric hunting kit appeared, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda voietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Lviva-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects on the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Transitional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polish Towarzysto Astronautique) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problem, in which four extensive articles of space travel were dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, there were the first satellite technology projects, and it was to be seen that the research of the universe would have a future.
In its early years in 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA sought to join the International Space Federation established in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimier Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was Vice-President of the International Federation for Space Navigation.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been involved in the development of the most successful meteorological rockets (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), the first Polish rockets for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and began in 1959 in the Błędów Desert Flight Tests with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rockets should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used to monitor high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was slowed down.
A successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) of this rocket have been developed, which differ in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km at all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 rockets were developed at the airport, the first of which began flight testing in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites in the intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut in the Czech state of Vladimir Remek.
